aa(lp92
VYears ago, my colleagues and I embarked on a study
p93
aVwhere we followed the same group of people over a 10-year period.
p94
aVOriginally, the sample was aged 18 to 94.
p95
aVAnd we studied whether and how their emotional experiences changed
p96
aVas they grew older.
p97
aVOur participants would carry electronic pagers
p98
aVfor a week at a time,
p99
aVand we'd page them throughout the day and evenings at random times.
p100
aVAnd every time we paged them,
p101
aVwe'd ask them to answer several questions \u2014
p102
aV"On a one to seven scale, how happy are you right now?"
p103
aV"How sad are you right now?"
p104
aV"How frustrated are you right now?" \u2014
p105
aVso that we could get a sense of the kinds of emotions and feelings they were having
p106
aVin their day-to-day lives.
p107
aa(lp108
VAnd using this intense study of individuals,
p109
aVwe find that it's not one particular generation
p110
aVthat's doing better than the others,
p111
aVbut the same individuals over time
p112
aVcome to report relatively greater positive experience.
p113
aVNow you see this slight downturn at very advanced ages.
p114
aVAnd there is a slight downturn.
p115
aVBut at no point does it return to the levels we see in early adulthood.
p116
aa(lp117
VNow it's really too simplistic to say that older people are "happy."
p118
aVIn our study, they are more positive.
p119
aVBut they're also more likely than younger people
p120
aVto experience mixed emotions \u2014
p121
aVsadness at the same time you experience happiness;
p122
aVyou know, that tear in the eye when you're smiling at a friend.
p123
aVAnd other research has shown that older people seem to engage with sadness
p124
aVmore comfortably.
p125
aVThey're more accepting of sadness than younger people are.
p126
aVAnd we suspect that this may help to explain
p127
aVwhy older people are better than younger people
p128
aVat solving hotly charged emotional conflicts and debates.
p129
aVOlder people can view injustice with compassion,
p130
aVbut not despair.
p131
aa(lp132
VAnd all things being equal,
p133
aVolder people direct their cognitive resources, like attention and memory,
p134
aVto positive information more than negative.
p135
aVIf we show older, middle-aged, younger people images,
p136
aVlike the ones you see on the screen,
p137
aVand we later ask them to recall all the images that they can,
p138
aVolder people, but not younger people,
p139
aVremember more positive images than negative images.
p140
aVWe've asked older and younger people to view faces in laboratory studies,
p141
aVsome frowning, some smiling.
p142
aVOlder people look toward the smiling faces and away from the frowning, angry faces.
p143
aVIn day-to-day life, this translates into greater enjoyment and satisfaction.
